## 🧠 2. **`useParams`**

👉 Best when you **just need the URL value**, not fetching automatically.
👉 You can use the param to do *anything you want* inside the component (fetch, display, logic, etc.).

### 📌 Real-life Example → **Product Page with Manual Fetch**

Route: `/products/:productId`
We want to **fetch the product inside the component** instead of using loader.

#### 🧭 Route Setup

```jsx
import { createBrowserRouter, RouterProvider } from "react-router-dom";
import ProductPage from "./ProductPage";

const router = createBrowserRouter([
  { path: "/products/:productId", element: <ProductPage /> },
]);

export default function App() {
  return <RouterProvider router={router} />;
}
```

#### 📄 ProductPage.jsx

```jsx
import { useParams } from "react-router-dom";
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";

export default function ProductPage() {
  const { productId } = useParams();
  const [product, setProduct] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch(`https://fakestoreapi.com/products/${productId}`)
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => setProduct(data));
  }, [productId]);

  if (!product) return <p>Loading...</p>;

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{product.title}</h2>
      <p>{product.description}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

✅ **Why use here:** You want **full control** over when and how to fetch data. Great for pages where data might **change based on user interaction**.

---

## 🧠 3. **`useEffect`**

👉 Best for **non-route-based** or **on-demand** data fetching.
👉 Useful for things like **search**, **filters**, **dashboards**, or **components that fetch independently** of routing.

### 📌 Real-life Example → **Search Bar Component**

Not tied to any URL params — just fetch data when user types.

```jsx
import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

export default function SearchBar() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState("");
  const [results, setResults] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (query.length > 2) {
      fetch(`https://api.example.com/search?q=${query}`)
        .then(res => res.json())
        .then(data => setResults(data.items));
    }
  }, [query]);

  return (
    <div>
      <input
        type="text"
        placeholder="Search..."
        value={query}
        onChange={(e) => setQuery(e.target.value)}
      />
      <ul>
        {results.map((r) => (
          <li key={r.id}>{r.name}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}
```

✅ **Why use here:** It’s not tied to the router. Data changes dynamically when the user interacts.

