# Step 7— (Optional but recommended) Server-side verification

Client tokens can be spoofed; for production verify with the **Secret Key** server-side.

Example Node.js/Express endpoint:

```js
// /verify-recaptcha POST { token }
const express = require('express');
const axios = require('axios');
const app = express();
app.use(express.json());

app.post('/verify-recaptcha', async (req, res) => {
  const token = req.body.token;
  const secret = process.env.RECAPTCHA_SECRET; // keep secret safe in env var

  try {
    const resp = await axios.post(`https://www.google.com/recaptcha/api/siteverify`, null, {
      params: { secret, response: token }
    });
    const data = resp.data;
    // For v2: data.success === true
    // For v3: check data.score >= threshold (e.g., 0.5)
    if (data.success) return res.json({ ok: true });
    return res.status(403).json({ ok: false, data });
  } catch (err) {
    return res.status(500).json({ ok: false, err: err.message });
  }
});
```

Flow: Client gets token (v3) or onChange (v2) → sends token to backend `/verify-recaptcha` → backend verifies with Google → returns ok → then backend calls Firebase Admin APIs or allows frontend to call Firebase.

---

# Step 8 — Testing locally & deploying

* Locally: Add `localhost` as allowed domain in the reCAPTCHA admin panel. Use the site key provided.
* Production: add production hostnames. Remember Google will block keys used on domains not listed.
* For v3: include `<script src="https://www.google.com/recaptcha/api.js?render=SITE_KEY"></script>` or call `grecaptcha.execute`.

---

# Troubleshooting / FAQs

* **“Captcha disappears before I verify”** — ensure you’re not conditionally hiding it by mistake. Only hide after `onChange` fires.
* **“Token expired / verification fails”** — tokens are short-lived. Retry or re-render widget.
* **“Domain invalid”** — when registering keys, use only hostnames (`localhost`, `example.com`), not URLs with protocol or ports.
* **“I want invisible UX”** — use **v3**; you must evaluate scores server-side and set an accept threshold.

---

# Security best practices

1. Always verify tokens server-side for high-value flows (password resets, payments).
2. Keep the **Secret Key** off the client — store in environment variables.
3. Rate-limit and/or backoff repeated attempts server-side.
4. Consider enabling Firebase **App Check** for added protection of backend resources.
